snippet.textDisplay: Another thing about Anton Chigurh that isn't mentioned in the movie of No Country for Old Men but is mentioned in the book is about how Anton explains that he let himself be arrested at the beginning. He "allowed" it to happen. Essentially to see if fate would present him with an opportunity to find means of an escape of the situation. That right there is rather frightening if you think about it. He's so devoid of basic humanity that he willingly let himself be put into chains just to see if the chains or circumstance could hold him.... Or stop him. He couldn't be stopped.
